#
# PGSD-DEBUG -- Debug variant of the PGSD kernel configuration.
#
# Derives from PGSD via include(5) to inherit every device, option,
# and makeoption decision; adds the debug-kernel options block. Use
# this kernconf during development of kernel-side PGSD components
# (drawfs, inputfs, AD-28's planned inputfs_kbdmux bridge, etc.) so
# that lock-order violations, mutex misuse, and uninitialized-lock
# bugs are caught at the moment of occurrence with a backtrace
# rather than silently corrupting state or deadlocking later.
#
# The runtime cost is significant: WITNESS in particular adds
# overhead to every mutex acquire; the FreeBSD handbook quotes 5-10x
# slowdown on lock-heavy workloads. PGSD-DEBUG is for development
# only; production deployments use PGSD.
#
# Build procedure: see pgsd-kernel/README.md "Building a debug
# kernel". The WITHOUT_MODULES list from PGSD's main build
# procedure must be passed unchanged to keep ADR 0018 §3a's
# "inputfs is the exclusive HID consumer" invariant intact;
# PGSD-DEBUG does not relax which devices are absent from the
# kernel, only which assertions and lock-tracking are present.
#
# Post-reboot verification:
#   sysctl debug.witness.watch       (expect: 1)
#   sysctl debug.witness.skipspin    (expect: 1)
#   sysctl kern.conftxt | grep -E '^options (WITNESS|INVARIANTS|DDB)$'
#   uname -i                         (expect: PGSD-DEBUG)
#
# To return to the production kernel:
#   sudo nextboot -k kernel.PGSD     (if installed alongside)
#   or boot via the loader prompt: boot kernel.PGSD/kernel
#
# Per docs/DF4_VERIFICATION.md, the debug kernel is also the
# verification environment for drawfs's locking discipline (DF-4).
# AD-28 (kbdmux bridge) extends the same justification: kernel
# code that reaches into kbd.c (which is GIANT_REQUIRED almost
# everywhere) is exactly the kind of integration where a
# silent lock-order violation under stock PGSD becomes an obvious
# WITNESS finding here.
#

include "PGSD"

ident		PGSD-DEBUG

# Interactive kernel debugger. PGSD already has KDB (the framework)
# and KDB_TRACE (panic backtraces). DDB is the front-end that lets
# you examine memory, set breakpoints, and run `bt` interactively
# from a serial console after a panic or a manual `sysctl
# debug.kdb.enter=1`. Without DDB, a panic just halts; with DDB,
# the kernel drops into a prompt where the failure can be
# investigated.
options 	DDB

# WITNESS — runtime lock-order tracking. Every mutex acquisition
# is checked against an inferred global lock-order graph; cycles
# (potential deadlocks) are reported with a backtrace at the
# moment they're introduced, not when they actually deadlock.
# This is the single most valuable debug option for kernel work
# that crosses subsystem boundaries.
options 	WITNESS

# WITNESS_SKIPSPIN — exclude spin mutexes from WITNESS tracking.
# Spin mutexes have stricter rules (no sleeping, no nested sleep
# locks) but their lock-order graph is verified at compile time
# in the scheduler core; tracking them at runtime adds large
# overhead without finding new bugs. The standard recommendation
# for development kernels.
options 	WITNESS_SKIPSPIN

# INVARIANTS / INVARIANT_SUPPORT — kernel-internal assertions.
# Many subsystems wrap consistency checks in KASSERT() macros
# that compile to nothing without these options. Enabling them
# turns a class of "should never happen" bugs from silent
# corruption into immediate panics with a clear message.
# INVARIANT_SUPPORT is a prerequisite for INVARIANTS and for
# certain third-party modules that test for it.
options 	INVARIANTS
options 	INVARIANT_SUPPORT

# DEADLKRES — deadlock resolver. Periodically scans for threads
# that have been blocked on the same lock for too long and
# panics with the offending lock chain. Catches deadlocks that
# WITNESS's static analysis misses (e.g. lock-order violations
# in code paths the analysis didn't reach). Cheap; recommended
# alongside WITNESS.
options 	DEADLKRES

# MALLOC_DEBUG_MAXZONES=8 — split the kernel malloc(9) zones into
# 8 buckets to make use-after-free bugs more visible. Without
# this, freed memory can be reallocated immediately and the
# corruption is invisible; with this, freed memory is more
# likely to remain in a state that triggers detectable
# inconsistencies. The value 8 is the standard development
# choice.
options 	MALLOC_DEBUG_MAXZONES=8
